😂 Bolt is on demon time, but his security take here is mostly solid.

Did you sacrifice security to make it work?

Net: no — not if the proxy now requires a valid Supabase session and returns 401 otherwise. That change closes the only real immediate hole (public relay).

Where I still agree with your “works and good” standard:

1) The CORS wildcard is the easiest real win

Bolt’s right: even with auth required, Access-Control-Allow-Origin: * is sloppy because it lets any origin attempt calls (and if a user is signed in, that origin can potentially succeed in a browser context depending on how you handle credentials/headers).

Best practice: allow only your known origins:

Prod: https://<yourdomain>

Dev: http://localhost:5173 (or whatever port)

Tight CORS pattern for a Supabase Edge Function (Deno)

Use a small allowlist and reflect the origin only if it’s allowed:

const ALLOWED_ORIGINS = new Set([
  "http://localhost:5173",
  "https://your-prod-domain.com",
  // add staging if you have it
]);

function corsHeaders(req: Request) {
  const origin = req.headers.get("origin") ?? "";
  const allowed = ALLOWED_ORIGINS.has(origin);

  return {
    ...(allowed ? { "Access-Control-Allow-Origin": origin } : {}),
    "Access-Control-Allow-Methods": "GET,POST,PUT,PATCH,DELETE,OPTIONS",
    "Access-Control-Allow-Headers": "authorization, x-client-info, apikey, content-type, x-github-token",
    "Access-Control-Allow-Credentials": "true",
    "Vary": "Origin",
  };
}


And handle preflight:

if (req.method === "OPTIONS") {
  return new Response("ok", { headers: corsHeaders(req) });
}


✅ That’s the “tighten it now” improvement that doesn’t add complexity.

2) Token-through-client is “OK,” not “great”

Bolt’s point about “personal tool” is fair, but the exposure surface is real:

token is visible in devtools network tab

if you ever add extensions / logging / error tooling, it can leak

The “good” next step (without going full enterprise):

keep Supabase Auth GitHub provider

don’t pass X-GitHub-Token from browser on every call

instead: call an edge function that reads the user session, and either:

uses the provider_token if available, or

stores it once encrypted server-side

But you’re totally fine to ship with “OK” for now if it’s locked behind auth + tight CORS + no logs.

3) verify_jwt: false + manual validation

Bolt’s also right here: if you are truly validating the Supabase JWT inside the function (and rejecting invalid/expired tokens), then security-wise it’s equivalent to verify_jwt: true.

The only gotcha: people sometimes “manual validate” by just checking a header exists, or calling getUser() incorrectly. So it’s worth ensuring it’s real validation.

The most reliable manual validation pattern

Inside the Edge Function:

require Authorization: Bearer <token>

create Supabase client with that bearer and call auth.getUser()

reject if no user

That’s enough.